text.text:
Can you smell that? It's the smell of burgeoning flowers, aromatic herbs and freshly mowed grass. It's the scent of a community coming together to plant seedlings and grow crops, it's the whiff of companionship and an antidote to all that negative juju floating about. 

It's horticultural therapy, baby, it's free, it's filthy and it makes this city look really lovely. So why not get involved and become a community G?

tip.text:
There's nothing quite like sitting under a rose-covered pergola with a good book, your bae or a nice warm brew. And what a pergola this lovely community garden in Islington has to offer. Set up in 1982, the Culpeper Garden focuses on organic growing and features a lawn, a pond, veg beds, retro brick seating, luscious perennials and a plethora of cool events throughout the summer - think drawing workshops and hanging basket master classes. Come for a lazy stroll, and for god's sake leave your phone in your pocket. Just this once.

This is possibly the most romantic community garden in London, thanks to the love, care and attention volunteers put into it. If you want to get involved, join in on one of their open volunteer sessions, which take place every Tuesday between 2-4pm or every Friday between 11-1pm. If you're too busy to make it (you work, we hear ya), then head to one of their community workdays on the second Sunday of each month. No need to let anyone know, just pack your green fingers and show up.

tip.text:
We know, we know, the name is misleading, but you could probably grow an elephant here if you really wanted to - though you'd need to have very little respect for nature, animals, the environment, the world, and we know you're not that kind of person. Instead, the people of Elephant and Castle have come together to grow fresh veg and summery flowers in movable raised beds, so those green fingers can run wild when you're not busy enjoying a warm cuppa from the on-site caff.

They also host regular events throughout summer - like workshops, live gigs, outdoor film screenings, yoga classes and poetry nights - and keep a small part of the garden sectioned off for volunteers to grow their own veg and relax. Just don't forget to bring some tweezers, pallet seating can get annoying.

There's at least one volunteering session per week, just email Paul to find out when.

tip.text:
How can a garden be nomadic, we hear you ask. The answer is simple: you plant it in raised beds, to avoid ground contamination and ensure your little garden can go wherever you go - if you know someone with a van, of course. That's the spirit behind the Nomadic Community Garden currently residing in the shabby-chic pastures of Shoreditch, which invites local residents to enjoy a spot of gardening during the day, or sit back and indulge in some chill vibes and live music at night.

It features over 100 flower beds made out of pallets, kooky artsy sculptures, graffitied walls, makeshift seats by the fire and a small caff on the back of a scooter - because, well, it's Shoreditch innit. It's undeniably one of the most buzzing community spots in East London, with block parties, workshops, DJs and events going on all through summer. Volunteers are welcome any time, any day, so really you've got no excuse not to pop by and muck in.

text.text:
The problem with gardens is that you can't just take them with you wherever you go. Unless your garden is nomadic, obvs. Currently residing in the shabby-chic pastures of Shoreditch, this kooky garden is all about planting in raised beds and enjoying some live music and chill vibes come evening. It features over 100 flower beds made out of pallets; kooky, artsy sculptures; graffitied walls; makeshift seats by the fire and a small cafe on the back of a scooter - because, well, Shoreditch.

Get involved: Volunteers are welcome any time, any day, so really you've got no excuse not to pop by and muck in.

tip.text:
A glossy pic of this unique oasis is what you’ll find when you look up the words ‘pure’, ‘magic’ and ‘heart-warmingly beautiful’ in the Dojo dictionary. Yeah, our dictionary has pictures. Sitting on the old Eastern Curve railway line, entering the covert door here is akin to walking through the wardrobe to Narnia - minus the talking animals, mythical creatures and foreboding sense of danger. Instead you’ve got plants, wood-chippings, fairy lights and a friendly crowd of locals basking in Dalston’s version of heaven.

The long, curved garden features plants, veggies and herbs; a cafe that also sells beers, wine and homemade soups; a stage for live music; and a pizza oven doing £6 pies. This is truly a community place with a wealth of programmes and workshops aimed at helping isolated people. Chilling with some pals beneath the tree-top canopy as the evening draws in is one of London’s true pleasures.

text.text:
Look, we're gonna level with you, we're quite into curves. All curves. Yes, even your curves. But curvy gardens are especially enticing, because according to the Chinese art of feng shui, rounded curvatures channel the universe's energy to flow around your garden. Only this little East End woodland was named the Dalston Curve not because it's curvy, but because it sits on the old Eastern Curve railway line. See, you learn something new and vaguely interesting everyday.

Get involved: Volunteers can drop in every Saturday between 2-5pm until winter.

tip.text:
The Queen's Wood Cafe is like a beacon of light at the end of the long, gritty, urban tunnel that is London. This place makes it very easy to pretend you're chilling at a friend's country home instead of smack dab in a gigantic metropolitan centre. Located right by Highgate Wood, we can't stress the cabin feels of this spot quite enough.

Billing itself as a community cafe, the menu features all the healthy comfort foods you'd expect from such a provincial venture: hearty breakfasts, quiches, organic soups, even a kid's meal. Naturally, everything is sourced locally and sustainably. There's even a lush garden to boot, maintained by volunteers.

text.text:
Apple trees, bee hives, veggies in the garden, a chalet-style cafe hidden in the woods - this spot gives us those warm and fuzzy eco-feels that are all the rage right now. So why not pop in before your gig at Ally Pally and see what these volunteer gardeners have been doing. Or better yet, taste it, as you can eat what they reap at the Queen's Wood Cafe. Bring a good book and your dog - it's time to indulge in some you time. We reckon you've earned it. 

Get involved: Volunteer sessions take place on Mondays and Thursdays from 9am to 1pm. Plant sales are also often held on weekends.

tip.text:
In a bid to counteract the corporate dullness swooping across King's Cross, the good folk of Global Generation - a charity that works with young people to create a sustainable future - have come together to create this little urban oasis housed within a bunch of skips.

This portable 'garden of 1000 hands' - after the 1000 volunteers who helped to build it, though technically that would be 2000 hands - is the perfect example of what organic farming can look like in the heart of the metropolis. It plays host to wild flowers, organic veg, beehives, a veggie kitchen, chicken coops, a recycled glass tower and a strange gramophone which beams the sound of the beehive (a beemaphone, surely?)

The Skip Garden welcomes volunteers anytime during its opening hours, and a weekly twilight gardening session takes place on Wednesday nights from 5-7pm during Summer - so pop in after work and get involved.

tip.text:
Olden gardens are the best, especially when you consider that a youngen garden would essentially just be a bunch of young shoots and seedlings. Lucky for us, this luscious two-acre community garden in Highbury boasts over 25 years of growing, pollinating, self-seeding and blossoming, along with a cosy summer house for when summer isn't feeling especially summery.

The OG also features a small woodland, a greenhouse, an apple and plum orchard, a wildflower meadow and a colourful array of burgeoning allotments - focusing on sustainable, organic food productions and horticultural training for the non-oldens among us. Volunteer days are on the third Saturday of every month, or you could pay £20 and become a member, as all funds go towards the upkeep of this lovely spot of greenery.

tip.text:
If you're the type of person who wouldn't miss BBC's Gardener's World for, well, the world, then chances are you've been gagging for a greenhouse for years. Because the truth is, these genius contraptions are hotbeds for all sorts of medicinal, edible and exotic plants which simply wouldn't stand a chance in London's great, grey outdoors.

Which is why the good people of Brockwell have gotten together to grow some tasty stuff in the vast greenhouses of Brockwell Park. Here they plant seeds, take cuttings, propagate, harvest, cook and sell some of their favourite earthly specimens - like yam, banana, chilli, ginger or cocoa. When the weather is nice, volunteers will plant new shoots in the park's grounds, have a picnic in the woodland or nurture the pond's extensive wildlife. When the weather is not so nice, it's fine, because they have a bloody greenhouse.

Volunteers are welcome any time during the park's opening times - closing at 5pm during summer and 4pm come winter.

tip.text:
This is one of those integral community gardens that, frankly, should be found in every single neighbourhood. Calthorpe Project is a small green oasis of calm in the heart of King's Cross; a multi-purpose space offering that peace, that tranquility, that sense of community that everyone needs, no matter how big and tough they might make out.

Set up with the aim of improving the physical and emotional well-being of those who live, work or study in Camden, this is home to a horticultural volunteering programme, food growing, a vegetarian cafe and a 5-a-side futsal pitch. The cafe does toasties, salads and spinach and feta pies to keep things ticking over. There's even beer for sale and a pizza oven in use come Friday evenings in the summer. Not the biggest community garden you'll come across, but one with a big old heart.
